<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Treasury pointed out that Viceroy is not regulated in South Africa, and that by its own admission, has been trading [short selling] in Capitec shares ahead of the release of its report."It stood to benefit largely from forcing the Capitec share price to fall by publishing its speculative report about the bank," In its statement, Treasury said Viceroy operated anonymously and opaquely.“The reckless way in which it has released its report is clear proof that it is not acting in the public interest nor in the interest of financial stability in South Africa. Whilst the Treasury expects prudential and market conduct regulators in South Africa to consider all relevant reports in the public domain, and to act where any risks or wrongdoing in the law are identified, Treasury is of the view that the Viceroy report provides no basis to put any bank under curatorship,” Treasury added.